  {"domain":"Science","skill":"Evaluation of Models","type":"mc","text":"<em style=\"font-weight:400; font-size:0.85em; line-height:1.7; display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;\">Study 5: Scientist 1 argues the dinosaur extinction 66 million years ago was caused primarily by an asteroid impact, citing a worldwide layer of iridium — an element rare on Earth but common in asteroids — laid down at exactly that time. Scientist 2 argues massive volcanic eruptions in the Deccan Traps drove the extinction through gradual climate change, noting the eruptions began before the impact and released enormous volumes of climate-altering gases. Both agree the extinction was geologically rapid.</em>Scientist 2 attributes the extinction primarily to","choices":["sea-level rise alone.","gradual climate change from massive volcanism.","a single asteroid impact.","disease."],"correct":1},
  {"domain":"Science","skill":"Evaluation of Models","type":"mc","text":"<em style=\"font-weight:400; font-size:0.85em; line-height:1.7; display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;\">Study 5: Scientist 1 argues the dinosaur extinction 66 million years ago was caused primarily by an asteroid impact, citing a worldwide layer of iridium — an element rare on Earth but common in asteroids — laid down at exactly that time. Scientist 2 argues massive volcanic eruptions in the Deccan Traps drove the extinction through gradual climate change, noting the eruptions began before the impact and released enormous volumes of climate-altering gases. Both agree the extinction was geologically rapid.</em>The two scientists agree that","choices":["the extinction occurred about 66 million years ago and was geologically rapid.","iridium comes from volcanoes.","the Deccan Traps never erupted.","dinosaurs survived the event."],"correct":0},
  {"domain":"Science","skill":"Evaluation of Models","type":"mc","text":"<em style=\"font-weight:400; font-size:0.85em; line-height:1.7; display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;\">Study 5: Scientist 1 argues the dinosaur extinction 66 million years ago was caused primarily by an asteroid impact, citing a worldwide layer of iridium — an element rare on Earth but common in asteroids — laid down at exactly that time. Scientist 2 argues massive volcanic eruptions in the Deccan Traps drove the extinction through gradual climate change, noting the eruptions began before the impact and released enormous volumes of climate-altering gases. Both agree the extinction was geologically rapid.</em>Which finding would most strengthen Scientist 1?","choices":["Eruptions lasted a million years.","Iridium is common in Earth’s crust.","Some dinosaurs were small.","Impact debris found directly beneath the first extinction-level fossil losses worldwide."],"correct":3},
  {"domain":"Science","skill":"Evaluation of Models","type":"mc","text":"<em style=\"font-weight:400; font-size:0.85em; line-height:1.7; display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;\">Study 5: Scientist 1 argues the dinosaur extinction 66 million years ago was caused primarily by an asteroid impact, citing a worldwide layer of iridium — an element rare on Earth but common in asteroids — laid down at exactly that time. Scientist 2 argues massive volcanic eruptions in the Deccan Traps drove the extinction through gradual climate change, noting the eruptions began before the impact and released enormous volumes of climate-altering gases. Both agree the extinction was geologically rapid.</em>Which finding would most weaken Scientist 2?","choices":["Evidence that asteroids contain iridium.","Evidence the climate changed.","Evidence that most Deccan gas release occurred well after the extinction.","Evidence of any volcanic activity."],"correct":2},
  {"domain":"Science","skill":"Scientific Investigation","type":"mc","text":"<em style=\"font-weight:400; font-size:0.85em; line-height:1.7; display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;\">Study 5: Scientist 1 argues the dinosaur extinction 66 million years ago was caused primarily by an asteroid impact, citing a worldwide layer of iridium — an element rare on Earth but common in asteroids — laid down at exactly that time. Scientist 2 argues massive volcanic eruptions in the Deccan Traps drove the extinction through gradual climate change, noting the eruptions began before the impact and released enormous volumes of climate-altering gases. Both agree the extinction was geologically rapid.</em>The most direct way to test between the models is to","choices":["survey living reptiles.","precisely date the extinction, the impact, and the peak eruptions relative to one another.","count modern volcano eruptions.","simulate asteroid orbits today."],"correct":1},
  {"domain":"Science","skill":"Scientific Investigation","type":"mc","text":"<em style=\"font-weight:400; font-size:0.85em; line-height:1.7; display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;\">Study 5: Scientist 1 argues the dinosaur extinction 66 million years ago was caused primarily by an asteroid impact, citing a worldwide layer of iridium — an element rare on Earth but common in asteroids — laid down at exactly that time. Scientist 2 argues massive volcanic eruptions in the Deccan Traps drove the extinction through gradual climate change, noting the eruptions began before the impact and released enormous volumes of climate-altering gases. Both agree the extinction was geologically rapid.</em>Scientist 2’s note that eruptions “began before the impact” is used to argue that","choices":["climate stress was already underway independent of the asteroid.","the asteroid caused the eruptions.","iridium is volcanic.","the impact never occurred."],"correct":0},
  {"domain":"Science","skill":"Interpretation of Data","type":"mc","text":"<em style=\"font-weight:400; font-size:0.85em; line-height:1.7; display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;\">Study 6: Researchers measured a river on one summer day at four sites, upstream to downstream. Dissolved oxygen (DO, mg/L) and water temperature: Site A — 12 mg/L, 14°C; Site B — 10 mg/L, 17°C; Site C — 8 mg/L, 21°C; Site D — 6 mg/L, 24°C. Trout require DO above 8 mg/L.</em>Dissolved oxygen at Site C was","choices":["12 mg/L","6 mg/L","10 mg/L","8 mg/L"],"correct":3},
  {"domain":"Science","skill":"Interpretation of Data","type":"mc","text":"<em style=\"font-weight:400; font-size:0.85em; line-height:1.7; display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;\">Study 6: Researchers measured a river on one summer day at four sites, upstream to downstream. Dissolved oxygen (DO, mg/L) and water temperature: Site A — 12 mg/L, 14°C; Site B — 10 mg/L, 17°C; Site C — 8 mg/L, 21°C; Site D — 6 mg/L, 24°C. Trout require DO above 8 mg/L.</em>The data show that as temperature increased, dissolved oxygen","choices":["was unaffected.","fluctuated randomly.","decreased.","increased."],"correct":2},
  {"domain":"Science","skill":"Interpretation of Data","type":"mc","text":"<em style=\"font-weight:400; font-size:0.85em; line-height:1.7; display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;\">Study 6: Researchers measured a river on one summer day at four sites, upstream to downstream. Dissolved oxygen (DO, mg/L) and water temperature: Site A — 12 mg/L, 14°C; Site B — 10 mg/L, 17°C; Site C — 8 mg/L, 21°C; Site D — 6 mg/L, 24°C. Trout require DO above 8 mg/L.</em>A fifth site downstream of D at 26°C would most likely have DO","choices":["about 10 mg/L","below 6 mg/L","above 12 mg/L","exactly 8 mg/L"],"correct":1},
  {"domain":"Science","skill":"Interpretation of Data","type":"mc","text":"<em style=\"font-weight:400; font-size:0.85em; line-height:1.7; display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;\">Study 6: Researchers measured a river on one summer day at four sites, upstream to downstream. Dissolved oxygen (DO, mg/L) and water temperature: Site A — 12 mg/L, 14°C; Site B — 10 mg/L, 17°C; Site C — 8 mg/L, 21°C; Site D — 6 mg/L, 24°C. Trout require DO above 8 mg/L.</em>Based on the trout requirement, which sites could support trout?","choices":["A and B only","all four sites","C and D only","none of the sites"],"correct":0},
  {"domain":"Science","skill":"Scientific Investigation","type":"mc","text":"<em style=\"font-weight:400; font-size:0.85em; line-height:1.7; display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;\">Study 6: Researchers measured a river on one summer day at four sites, upstream to downstream. Dissolved oxygen (DO, mg/L) and water temperature: Site A — 12 mg/L, 14°C; Site B — 10 mg/L, 17°C; Site C — 8 mg/L, 21°C; Site D — 6 mg/L, 24°C. Trout require DO above 8 mg/L.</em>Measuring all four sites on the same day helps ensure that","choices":["the river flows faster.","trout are present.","equipment stays dry.","weather differences between days do not confound the comparison."],"correct":3},
  {"domain":"Science","skill":"Scientific Investigation","type":"mc","text":"<em style=\"font-weight:400; font-size:0.85em; line-height:1.7; display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;\">Study 6: Researchers measured a river on one summer day at four sites, upstream to downstream. Dissolved oxygen (DO, mg/L) and water temperature: Site A — 12 mg/L, 14°C; Site B — 10 mg/L, 17°C; Site C — 8 mg/L, 21°C; Site D — 6 mg/L, 24°C. Trout require DO above 8 mg/L.</em>To increase confidence in the results, the researchers should","choices":["round all values to whole numbers.","sample only in winter.","repeat the measurements on multiple days.","measure only one site."],"correct":2},
  {"domain":"Science","skill":"Evaluation of Models","type":"mc","text":"<em style=\"font-weight:400; font-size:0.85em; line-height:1.7; display:block; margin-bottom:1rem;\">Study 6: Researchers measured a river on one summer day at four sites, upstream to downstream. Dissolved oxygen (DO, mg/L) and water temperature: Site A — 12 mg/L, 14°C; Site B — 10 mg/L, 17°C; Site C — 8 mg/L, 21°C; Site D — 6 mg/L, 24°C. Trout require DO above 8 mg/L.</em>The claim “warmer water holds more dissolved oxygen” is","choices":["true at Site A only.","contradicted by the data.","supported by the data.","not addressed by the data."],"correct":1}
